One of the foundation principles of hypertrophy is Progressive Overload. 

What is Progressive Overload? 🤷‍♂️

Progressive Overload means adding small increments of weight to stress the muscle beyond previous lifts, forcing it to adapt…by growing!

How do I apply it?🤷

Once you are able to complete a lift for your goal amount of reps…that is: to positive muscular failure…you add weight. This should be a very small amount - 2.5 to 5 pound plates are perfect. 

Important‼️

If your target reps is 10 and you only hit 8, do not add weight. Next workout try to hit 9 or 10 reps (adding reps is also progressive overload). Once you hit 10, add a small amount. 

Keep your rep tempo the same. That means if you are using a 1:1:3 rep tempo (1 second concentric, 1 sec squeeze, 3 sec eccentric) that should be the same tempo you use from workout to workout. Do not sacrifice tempo in order to lift heavier weights. You’re only cheating yourself as the progress is not real if you speed up the lift. 

Happy training!🏋️‍♀️

For years I've been stressing the importance of the anabolic window - that "magic" time when you can prime your body for maximum growth and recovery.

We used to think that post-workout was that time. After the gym we'd rush home, ignoring traffic lights, to quickly chow down on fast absorbing proteins and carbohydrates to get the most from our workouts.
